  "text": "Models are constructed from a set of branch clusters and optimized in the maximum likelihood framework. Models built from more than one subset are nonhomogeneous and are constructed as described in [CITATION_1] . Here we consider nonhomogeneous models derived from a single type of substitution matrix (e.g., Tamura 1992; Nielsen and Yang 1998), and only branch lengths and parameters of these substitution matrices are allowed to vary on a perbranch basis (θ for Tamura 1992, ω for [CITATION_2] . Despite these restrictions, such models encompass the vast majority of nonhomogeneous models used in the literature.",
